{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775886003190,"sessionID":"ses_284f280cfffe6MPI62wRcxkDml","part":{"id":"prt_d7b0debd3001vTl8XuD13bvEg5","messageID":"msg_d7b0de2b1001m2Wy3PYcU8Y4iw","sessionID":"ses_284f280cfffe6MPI62wRcxkDml","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_tool-244a8251538d468cbbbf9601bd95539f","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-034/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-034/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Delta Specification: AR-034 — CI/CD GitHub Actions (12 workflows)\n2: \n3: ## AR Metadata\n4: - **AR ID**: AR-034\n5: - **Title**: CI/CD GitHub Actions (12 workflows)\n6: - **Module**: .github\n7: - **Language**: YAML\n8: - **Size**: L\n9: - **Status**: Implementation Required\n10: \n11: ## Purpose\n12: This delta specification defines implementation requirements for 12 GitHub Actions workflows providing comprehensive CI/CD automation for the AgentCube project. The workflows cover build verification, linting, testing, code quality checks, end-to-end testing, Python SDK validation, container image publishing, dependency updates, and workflow approval mechanisms to ensure code quality and reliable continuous delivery.\n13: \n14: ## Requirements\n15: \n16: ### Requirement: CI workflow build verification\n17: The system SHALL build the Workload Manager Docker image on pull requests targeting `main` or `release-*` branches using Docker Buildx.\n18: \n19: #### Scenario: Docker build verification on pull request\n20: - **GIVEN** a pull request to `main` or `release-*` branch\n21: - **WHEN** the CI workflow job runs\n22: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL checkout the repository\n23: - **AND** Docker Buildx SHALL be set up with default builder instance\n24: - **AND** `docker` and `buildx` versions SHALL be verified and logged\n25: - **AND** `make docker-build` SHALL be executed successfully\n26: - **AND** the workflow SHALL report success if build completes\n27: \n28: #### Scenario: CI workflow triggers on correct branches\n29: - **GIVEN** the CI workflow configuration\n30: - **WHEN** a pull request is created\n31: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL trigger only for `main` branch\n32: - **AND** the workflow SHALL trigger only for branches matching `release-*` pattern\n33: - **AND** the workflow SHALL NOT trigger for other branches\n34: \n35: #### Scenario: CI workflow uses appropriate runner\n36: - **GIVEN** the CI workflow job configuration\n37: - **WHEN** the workflow runs\n38: - **THEN** the job SHALL use `ubuntu-latest` runner\n39: - **AND** the job SHALL have access to Docker\n40: \n41: #### Scenario: CI workflow failure handling\n42: - **GIVEN** the CI workflow with build step\n43: - **WHEN** `make docker-build` fails\n44: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL fail the job\n45: - **AND** the workflow SHALL report the failure in PR checks\n46: - **AND** the workflow SHALL provide error logs for debugging\n47: \n48: ### Requirement: Go lint workflow with path filtering\n49: The system SHALL run `make lint` (golangci-lint) when Go-related paths change on pull requests to `main` or `release-*` branches.\n50: \n51: #### Scenario: Path-filtered lint execution\n52: - **GIVEN** a pull request with changes to Go files\n53: - **WHEN** path filter matches `**/*.go`, `go.mod`, `go.sum`, `.golangci.yml`, or `.github/workflows/lint.yml`\n54: - **THEN** the Lint workflow SHALL run\n55: - **AND** Go version 1.24 SHALL be set up\n56: - **AND** `make lint` SHALL be executed\n57: - **AND** lint results SHALL be reported\n58: \n59: #### Scenario: Lint workflow skips on non-Go changes\n60: - **GIVEN** a pull request with only documentation changes\n61: - **WHEN** path filter does not match Go-related paths\n62: - **THEN** the Lint workflow SHALL skip execution\n63: - **AND** the workflow SHALL report success without running lint\n64: \n65: #### Scenario: Lint workflow reports Go lint errors\n66: - **GIVEN** the Lint workflow with golangci-lint execution\n67: - **WHEN** golangci-lint detects lint errors\n68: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL fail\n69: - **AND** lint errors SHALL be reported with file and line numbers\n70: - **AND** the PR SHALL show failing check status\n71: \n72: #### Scenario: Lint workflow passes on clean code\n73: - **GIVEN** the Lint workflow with clean Go code\n74: - **WHEN** golangci-lint completes without errors\n75: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL succeed\n76: - **AND** the PR SHALL show passing check status\n77: - **AND** lint summary SHALL be displayed\n78: \n79: ### Requirement: Code generation check workflow\n80: The system SHALL verify generated artifacts match `make gen-all` when API, hack, workflow, or Makefile inputs change on pull requests.\n81: \n82: #### Scenario: Codegen check on API changes\n83: - **GIVEN** a pull request with changes to `pkg/apis/**` directory\n84: - **WHEN** the Codegen Check workflow runs\n85: - **THEN** Go version 1.24.4 SHALL be set up\n86: - **AND** `make gen-check` SHALL be executed\n87: - **AND** the workflow SHALL verify no git diff exists after regeneration\n88: - **AND** the workflow SHALL fail if drift is detected\n89: \n90: #### Scenario: Codegen check on Makefile changes\n91: - **GIVEN** a pull request with changes to `Makefile`\n92: - **WHEN** the Codegen Check workflow runs\n93: - **THEN** `make gen-check` SHALL be executed\n94: - **AND** generated artifacts SHALL be regenerated\n95: - **AND** git diff SHALL be checked for changes\n96: - **AND** the workflow SHALL verify consistency\n97: \n98: #### Scenario: Codegen check on workflow changes\n99: - **GIVEN** a pull request with changes to `.github/workflows/**`\n100: - **WHEN** the Codegen Check workflow runs\n101: - **THEN** `make gen-check` SHALL be executed\n102: - **AND** workflow-generated artifacts SHALL be verified\n103: - **AND** the workflow SHALL ensure no drift\n104: \n105: #### Scenario: Codegen check failure on drift\n106: - **GIVEN** the Codegen Check workflow with detected drift\n107: - **WHEN** `git diff --exit-code` returns non-zero exit code\n108: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL fail\n109: - **AND** drift SHALL be reported to the user\n110: - **AND** instructions SHALL be provided to run `make gen-all`\n111: \n112: ### Requirement: Test coverage workflow with race detection\n113: The system SHALL run race-enabled coverage tests on `pkg/...` for qualifying pull requests and merge groups, uploading coverage reports as artifacts.\n114: \n115: #### Scenario: Coverage test execution\n116: - **GIVEN** a pull request or merge group triggering coverage path filter\n117: - **WHEN** the Test Coverage workflow runs\n118: - **THEN** Go version 1.24 SHALL be set up\n119: - **AND** free disk space SHALL be freed if needed\n120: - **AND** `go test -race -v -coverprofile=coverage.out -coverpkg=./pkg/... ./pkg/...` SHALL be executed\n121: - **AND** `coverage.out` SHALL be uploaded as artifact\n122: \n123: #### Scenario: Coverage path filtering\n124: - **GIVEN** the Test Coverage workflow configuration\n125: - **WHEN** path filter `coverage` matches (broad glob excluding media/docs)\n126: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL run for most code changes\n127: - **AND** the workflow SHALL skip for `*.md`, `*.svg`, `*.png` files\n128: - **AND** the workflow SHALL run for `**` pattern with exclusions\n129: \n130: #### Scenario: Coverage artifact upload\n131: - **GIVEN** the Test Coverage workflow with completed tests\n132: - **WHEN** coverage.out is generated\n133: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL upload `coverage.out` as artifact\n134: - **AND** artifact SHALL be retained for 30 days\n135: - **AND** artifact SHALL be downloadable for review\n136: \n137: #### Scenario: Coverage with Codecov integration\n138: - **GIVEN** the Test Coverage workflow with Codecov token secret\n139: - **WHEN** coverage tests complete successfully\n140: - **THEN** Codecov upload action SHALL be executed\n141: - **AND** coverage report SHALL be uploaded to Codecov\n142: - **AND** coverage percentage SHALL be displayed in PR comments\n143: \n144: #### Scenario: Coverage test failure handling\n145: - **GIVEN** the Test Coverage workflow with failing tests\n146: - **WHEN** `go test` returns non-zero exit code\n147: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL fail\n148: - **AND** test failures SHALL be reported with details\n149: - **AND** coverage.out SHALL still be uploaded if generated\n150: \n151: ### Requirement: E2E testing workflow on Kind\n152: The system SHALL run `make e2e` in CI using a Kind-capable Ubuntu runner, capturing logs on failure and ensuring cleanup.\n153: \n154: #### Scenario: E2E test execution\n155: - **GIVEN** a pull request to `main` or `release-*` branch\n156: - **WHEN** the E2E workflow runs\n157: - **THEN** `ARTIFACTS_PATH` SHALL be set to `${{ github.workspace }}/e2e-logs`\n158: - **AND** Kind tool v0.30.0 SHALL be installed with `install_only: true`\n159: - **AND** Go version 1.23 SHALL be set up\n160: - **AND** `make e2e` SHALL be executed\n161: - **AND** E2E tests SHALL run in Kind cluster\n162: \n163: #### Scenario: E2E test log capture on failure\n164: - **GIVEN** the E2E workflow with failing tests\n165: - **WHEN** `make e2e` fails\n166: - **THEN** `e2e-logs` directory SHALL be uploaded as artifact\n167: - **AND** artifact SHALL contain component logs and describes\n168: - **AND** logs SHALL be available for debugging\n169: \n170: #### Scenario: E2E test cleanup always runs\n171: - **GIVEN** the E2E workflow regardless of test outcome\n172: - **WHEN** tests complete (success or failure)\n173: - **THEN** `make e2e-clean` SHALL be executed in `always` condition\n174: - **AND** Kind cluster SHALL be deleted\n175: - **AND** temporary artifacts SHALL be cleaned up\n176: \n177: #### Scenario: E2E Kind cluster configuration\n178: - **GIVEN** the E2E workflow Kind setup\n179: - **WHEN** Kind is installed via `helm/kind-action@v1`\n180: - **THEN** version SHALL be v0.30.0\n181: - **AND** `install_only: true` SHALL prevent double cluster creation\n182: - **AND** cluster creation SHALL be handled by `run_e2e.sh`\n183: \n184: #### Scenario: E2E workflow uses appropriate runner\n185: - **GIVEN** the E2E workflow job configuration\n186: - **WHEN** the workflow runs\n187: - **THEN** the job SHALL use Ubuntu runner\n188: - **AND** the runner SHALL support Kind execution\n189: - **AND** sufficient resources SHALL be available for cluster\n190: \n191: ### Requirement: Python SDK unit tests workflow\n192: The system SHALL run pytest for the SDK when `sdk-python/**` changes on pull requests and merge groups.\n193: \n194: #### Scenario: Python SDK test execution\n195: - **GIVEN** a pull request with changes to `sdk-python/**` directory\n196: - **WHEN** the Python SDK Tests workflow runs\n197: - **THEN** Python version 3.12 SHALL be set up\n198: - **AND** working directory SHALL be `sdk-python/`\n199: - **AND** `pip install pytest` SHALL be executed\n200: - **AND** `pip install -e .` SHALL install SDK in editable mode\n201: - **AND** `python -m pytest tests/ -v` SHALL be executed\n202: \n203: #### Scenario: Python SDK path filtering\n204: - **GIVEN** the Python SDK Tests workflow configuration\n205: - **WHEN** path filter `sdk` matches `sdk-python/**`\n206: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL run for SDK changes\n207: - **AND** the workflow SHALL skip for non-SDK changes\n208: - **AND** the workflow SHALL use paths-filter action\n209: \n210: #### Scenario: Python SDK test failure reporting\n211: - **GIVEN** the Python SDK Tests workflow with failing tests\n212: - **WHEN** pytest detects test failures\n213: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL fail\n214: - **AND** test failures SHALL be reported with verbose output\n215: - **AND** failing tests SHALL be identified by name and traceback\n216: \n217: #### Scenario: Python SDK test passes\n218: - **GIVEN** the Python SDK Tests workflow with all tests passing\n219: - **WHEN** pytest completes successfully\n220: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL succeed\n221: - **AND** test summary SHALL be displayed\n222: - **AND** PR check SHALL show passing status\n223: \n224: ### Requirement: Python lint workflow\n225: The system SHALL run Ruff from repository root using `pyproject.toml` when Python-touching paths change.\n226: \n227: #### Scenario: Python lint execution\n228: - **GIVEN** a pull request with changes to Python files\n229: - **WHEN** path filter matches Python-related paths\n230: - **THEN** Python version 3.10 SHALL be set up\n231: - **AND** `pip install ruff` SHALL be executed\n232: - **AND** `python3 -m ruff check . --config pyproject.toml` SHALL be executed\n233: - **AND** lint SHALL check entire repository from root\n234: \n235: #### Scenario: Python lint path filtering\n236: - **GIVEN** the Python Lint workflow configuration\n237: - **WHEN** path filter `python` matches specified paths\n238: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL run for `cmd/cli/**` changes\n239: - **AND** the workflow SHALL run for `sdk-python/**` changes\n240: - **AND** the workflow SHALL run for `example/**` changes\n241: - **AND** the workflow SHALL run for `test/**/*.py` changes\n242: - **AND** the workflow SHALL run for `pyproject.toml` changes\n243: - **AND** the workflow SHALL run for workflow file changes\n244: \n245: #### Scenario: Python lint uses project configuration\n246: - **GIVEN** the Python Lint workflow execution\n247: - **WHEN** ruff is invoked\n248: - **THEN** `--config pyproject.toml` SHALL be passed\n249: - **AND** project-specific lint rules SHALL be applied\n250: - **AND** configuration SHALL be respected\n251: \n252: #### Scenario: Python lint error reporting\n253: - **GIVEN** the Python Lint workflow with lint errors\n254: - **WHEN** ruff detects lint issues\n255: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL fail\n256: - **AND** lint errors SHALL be reported with file and line numbers\n257: - **AND** error codes SHALL be displayed\n258: \n259: ### Requirement: Spelling check workflow with file exclusion\n260: The system SHALL run codespell on the repository for pull requests to `main` or `release-*`, temporarily moving files that cause false positives.\n261: \n262: #### Scenario: Codespell execution with file backup\n263: - **GIVEN** a pull request to `main` or `release-*` branch\n264: - **WHEN** the Codespell workflow runs\n265: - **THEN** `pip install codespell` SHALL be executed\n266: - **AND** `pyproject.toml`, `package-lock.json`, `package.json` SHALL be backed up or moved at repo root\n267: - **AND** nested copies SHALL be found and moved via `find`\n268: - **AND** codespell SHALL run with `--check-filenames`\n269: - **AND** skipped globs SHALL be applied\n270: - **AND** ignored words list `fo,nam,te,notin,NotIn` SHALL be applied\n271: - **AND** backed-up files SHALL be restored\n272: \n273: #### Scenario: Codespell configuration\n274: - **GIVEN** the Codespell workflow execution\n275: - **WHEN** codespell is invoked\n276: - **THEN** `--check-filenames` flag SHALL be used\n277: - **AND** `--skip` globs SHALL exclude specified patterns\n278: - **AND** `--ignore-words-list` SHALL include `fo,nam,te,notin,NotIn`\n279: - **AND** check SHALL run on `.` (current directory)\n280: \n281: #### Scenario: Codespell finds spelling errors\n282: - **GIVEN** the Codespell workflow with spelling errors\n283: - **WHEN** codespell detects misspelled words\n284: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL fail\n285: - **AND** spelling errors SHALL be reported with file and line\n286: - **AND** suggested corrections SHALL be displayed\n287: \n288: #### Scenario: Codespell passes on clean text\n289: - **GIVEN** the Codespell workflow with no spelling errors\n290: - **WHEN** codespell completes without issues\n291: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL succeed\n292: - **AND** PR check SHALL show passing status\n293: - **AND** file restore SHALL complete successfully\n294: \n295: ### Requirement: Copyright header check workflow\n296: The system SHALL ensure `make gen-copyright` produces no git diff when applicable files change.\n297: \n298: #### Scenario: Copyright check execution\n299: - **GIVEN** a pull request with changes triggering copyright path filter\n300: - **WHEN** the Copyright Check workflow runs\n301: - **THEN** `apt install moreutils` SHALL install sponge command\n302: - **AND** `make gen-copyright` SHALL be executed\n303: - **AND** `git diff --exit-code` SHALL verify no changes\n304: - **AND** the workflow SHALL succeed if no diff\n305: \n306: #### Scenario: Copyright path filtering\n307: - **GIVEN** the Copyright Check workflow configuration\n308: - **WHEN** path filter `copyright` matches\n309: - **THEN** the filter SHALL include all files except `*.md`\n310: - **AND** the filter SHALL exclude `*.svg` files\n311: - **AND** the filter SHALL exclude `*.png` files\n312: - **AND** the filter SHALL exclude `docs/**` directory\n313: - **AND** the filter SHALL exclude `.github/**` directory\n314: \n315: #### Scenario: Copyright check detects missing headers\n316: - **GIVEN** the Copyright Check workflow with files missing copyright\n317: - **WHEN** `make gen-copyright` adds headers\n318: - **THEN** `git diff` SHALL show changes\n319: - **AND** `git diff --exit-code` SHALL fail\n320: - **AND** the workflow SHALL fail\n321: - **AND** files needing headers SHALL be identified\n322: \n323: #### Scenario: Copyright check passes with proper headers\n324: - **GIVEN** the Copyright Check workflow with all files having headers\n325: - **WHEN** `make gen-copyright` completes\n326: - **THEN** `git diff` SHALL be empty\n327: - **AND** `git diff --exit-code` SHALL succeed\n328: - **AND** the workflow SHALL succeed\n329: \n330: ### Requirement: Release image publication workflow\n331: The system SHALL build and push multi-architecture images for workloadmanager, router, and picod to GitHub Container Registry on pushes to `main` and on semantic version tags.\n332: \n333: #### Scenario: Tag selection for image tags\n334: - **GIVEN** the Release workflow on `push` event\n335: - **WHEN** `github.ref_type` is `tag`\n336: - **THEN** `TAG` environment variable SHALL be set to `github.ref_name`\n337: - **AND** image SHALL be tagged with version from tag\n338: - **AND** workflow SHALL use semantic version as tag\n339: \n340: #### Scenario: Latest tag for main branch pushes\n341: - **GIVEN** the Release workflow on `push` to `main` branch\n342: - **WHEN** `github.ref_type` is not `tag`\n343: - **THEN** `TAG` environment variable SHALL be set to `latest`\n344: - **AND** image SHALL be tagged as `latest`\n345: - **AND** workflow SHALL push latest image\n346: \n347: #### Scenario: GHCR login and push\n348: - **GIVEN** the Release workflow with built images\n349: - **WHEN** images are ready to push\n350: - **THEN** `docker/login-action` SHALL login to `ghcr.io`\n351: - **AND** `GITHUB_TOKEN` SHALL be used for authentication\n352: - **AND** login SHALL succeed with proper permissions\n353: \n354: #### Scenario: Multi-architecture image build and push\n355: - **GIVEN** the Release workflow with Docker Buildx set up\n356: - **WHEN** building and pushing images\n357: - **THEN** `IMAGE_REGISTRY` SHALL be set to `ghcr.io/${{ github.repository_owner }}`\n358: - **AND** `make docker-buildx-push` SHALL build and push workloadmanager\n359: - **AND** `make docker-buildx-push-router` SHALL build and push router\n360: - **AND** `make docker-buildx-push-picod` SHALL build and push picod\n361: - **AND** each image SHALL support multiple architectures (amd64, arm64)\n362: - **AND** `*_IMAGE` variables SHALL include `:${TAG}` suffix\n363: \n364: #### Scenario: Release workflow triggers\n365: - **GIVEN** the Release workflow configuration\n366: - **WHEN** push occurs to `main` branch\n367: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL trigger\n368: - **AND** it SHALL build and push `latest` tagged images\n369: - **AND** push to `main` SHALL NOT trigger tag-based release\n370: \n371: #### Scenario: Semantic version tag triggers\n372: - **GIVEN** the Release workflow configuration\n373: - **WHEN** push creates tag matching `v*.*.*` or `v*.*.*-*`\n374: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL trigger\n375: - **AND** it SHALL build and push version-tagged images\n376: - **AND** tag SHALL be used as image tag\n377: \n378: #### Scenario: Release workflow uses Go 1.24.4\n379: - **GIVEN** the Release workflow job configuration\n380: - **WHEN** the workflow runs\n381: - **THEN** Go version 1.24.4 SHALL be set up\n382: - **AND** build SHALL use specified Go version\n383: - **AND** Go version SHALL match other workflows\n384: \n385: ### Requirement: Workflow approval for first-time contributors\n386: The system SHALL optionally approve pending workflow runs for pull requests from repeat contributors or those labeled `ok-to-test`.\n387: \n388: #### Scenario: Approve action_required for repeat contributors\n389: - **GIVEN** a `pull_request_target` event on `main` or `release-**`\n390: - **WHEN** contributor has more than one PR\n391: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL list workflow runs for head SHA\n392: - **AND** it SHALL filter for `action_required` status\n393: - **AND** it SHALL call `approveWorkflowRun` for each run\n394: - **AND** workflows SHALL be approved automatically\n395: \n396: #### Scenario: Approve with ok-to-test label\n397: - **GIVEN** a `pull_request_target` with `ok-to-test` label\n398: - **WHEN** labeled or synchronize events occur\n399: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL check for `ok-to-test` label\n400: - **AND** if label exists, workflows SHALL be approved\n401: - **AND** first-time contributors can use label to bypass wait\n402: \n403: #### Scenario: Skip approval for first-time contributors\n404: - **GIVEN** a `pull_request_target` from first-time contributor\n405: - **WHEN** contributor has only one PR and no `ok-to-test` label\n406: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL NOT approve workflows\n407: - **AND** workflows SHALL remain in `action_required` state\n408: - **AND** manual approval SHALL be required\n409: \n410: #### Scenario: Workflow approval triggers\n411: - **GIVEN** the Workflow Approval workflow configuration\n412: - **WHEN** `pull_request_target` events occur\n413: - **THEN** `labeled` event type SHALL trigger workflow\n414: - **AND** `synchronize` event type SHALL trigger workflow\n415: - **AND** target branches SHALL be `main` or `release-**`\n416: \n417: #### Scenario: GitHub API usage for approval\n418: - **GIVEN** the Workflow Approval workflow execution\n419: - **WHEN** approving workflow runs\n420: - **THEN** `github-script` action SHALL be used\n421: - **AND** it SHALL query GitHub API for workflow runs\n422: - **AND** it SHALL filter by head SHA and status\n423: - **AND** it SHALL call approval API for each run\n424: \n425: ### Requirement: Dependency update workflow\n426: The system SHALL periodically update Go and Python dependencies and create pull requests for review.\n427: \n428: #### Scenario: Scheduled dependency update\n429: - **GIVEN** the Dependency Update workflow configuration\n430: - **WHEN** scheduled time arrives (Monday UTC 0:00)\n431: - **THEN** `go get -u ./...` SHALL update Go dependencies\n432: - **AND** `go mod tidy` SHALL clean up go.mod and go.sum\n433: - **AND** `pip install --upgrade -r requirements.txt` SHALL update Python dependencies\n434: - **AND** tests SHALL be run to verify updates\n435: - **AND** Pull Request SHALL be created if changes exist\n436: \n437: #### Scenario: Manual dependency update trigger\n438: - **GIVEN** the Dependency Update workflow configuration\n439: - **WHEN** `workflow_dispatch` event is triggered manually\n440: - **THEN** the workflow SHALL run dependency updates\n441: - **AND** it SHALL follow same steps as scheduled run\n442: - **AND** it SHALL allow on-demand updates\n443: \n444: #### Scenario: Dependency update creates PR\n445: - **GIVEN** the Dependency Update workflow with dependency changes\n446: - **WHEN** updates are verified and tests pass\n447: - **THEN** a Pull Request SHALL be created\n448: - **AND** PR SHALL include all dependency changes\n449: - **AND** PR SHALL have `dependencies` label\n450: - **AND** PR description SHALL summarize updates\n451: \n452: #### Scenario: Dependency update verification\n453: - **GIVEN** the Dependency Update workflow after updates\n454: - **WHEN** dependencies are updated\n455: - **THEN** tests SHALL be executed to verify compatibility\n456: - **AND** test failures SHALL prevent PR creation\n457: - **AND** workflow SHALL fail if tests don't pass\n458: \n459: #### Scenario: No updates scenario\n460: - **GIVEN** the Dependency Update workflow execution\n461: - **WHEN** no dependency updates are available\n462: - **THEN** workflow SHALL complete successfully\n463: - **AND** no Pull Request SHALL be created\n464: - **AND** workflow SHALL report no changes\n465: \n466: #### Scenario: Dependency update branch management\n467: - **GIVEN** the Dependency Update workflow creating PR\n468: - **WHEN** preparing changes\n469: - **THEN** a new branch SHALL be created\n470: - **AND** branch name SHALL follow naming convention\n471: - **AND** changes SHALL be committed to branch\n472: - **AND** branch SHALL be pushed to remote\n473: \n474: ### Requirement: Workflow concurrency control\n475: The system SHALL use concurrency groups to cancel in-progress workflow runs when newer commits are pushed.\n476: \n477: #### Scenario: Concurrency group per workflow and ref\n478: - **GIVEN** a workflow with concurrency configured\n479: - **WHEN** multiple commits are pushed quickly\n480: - **THEN** concurrency group SHALL be `${{ github.workflow }}-${{ github.ref }}`\n481: - **AND** in-progress runs SHALL be cancelled\n482: - **AND** only latest run SHALL complete\n483: \n484: #### Scenario: Concurrency cancellation behavior\n485: - **GIVEN** an in-progress workflow run\n486: - **WHEN** a new commit triggers the same workflow\n487: - **THEN** older run SHALL be cancelled\n488: - **AND** newer run SHALL proceed\n489: - **AND** resources SHALL be freed from cancelled run\n490: \n491: #### Scenario: Concurrency for different branches\n492: - **GIVEN** workflow runs on different branches\n493: - **WHEN** runs occur concurrently\n494: - **THEN** runs SHALL NOT cancel each other\n495: - **AND** each branch SHALL have separate concurrency group\n496: - **AND** runs SHALL complete independently\n497: \n498: ### Requirement: Workflow caching strategy\n499: The system SHALL use GitHub Actions cache to speed up workflow execution by caching Go modules, Python packages, and Docker layers.\n500: \n501: #### Scenario: Go modules caching\n502: - **GIVEN** a workflow with Go dependency setup\n503: - **WHEN** cache action is configured\n504: - **THEN** cache path SHALL be `~/go/pkg/mod`\n505: - **THEN** cache key SHALL be `${{ runner.os }}-go-${{ hashFiles('**/go.sum') }}`\n506: - **AND** restore keys SHALL include `${{ runner.os }}-go-`\n507: - **AND** cache SHALL speed up dependency downloads\n508: \n509: #### Scenario: Python packages caching\n510: - **GIVEN** a workflow with Python dependency setup\n511: - **WHEN** cache action is configured\n512: - **THEN** cache path SHALL be `~/.cache/pip`\n513: - **AND** cache key SHALL be `${{ runner.os }}-pip-${{ hashFiles('**/requirements.txt') }}`\n514: - **AND** cache SHALL speed up pip installs\n515: \n516: #### Scenario: Docker layer caching\n517: - **GIVEN** a workflow with Docker Buildx\n518: - **WHEN** build cache is configured\n519: - **THEN** Docker layer cache SHALL be utilized\n520: - **AND** cache SHALL be stored in GitHub Actions cache\n521: - **AND** cache SHALL speed up image builds\n522: \n523: #### Scenario: Cache miss scenario\n524: - **GIVEN** a workflow with cache configuration\n525: - **WHEN** cache key does not match any existing cache\n526: - **THEN** cache SHALL be a miss\n527: - **AND** dependencies SHALL be downloaded normally\n528: - **AND** new cache SHALL be created after download\n529: \n530: ### Requirement: Workflow artifact management\n531: The system SHALL manage artifacts appropriately, uploading logs on failure and coverage reports always.\n532: \n533: #### Scenario: Upload coverage report artifact\n534: - **GIVEN** the Test Coverage workflow\n535: - **WHEN** `coverage.out` is generated\n536: - **THEN** artifact SHALL be uploaded with name `coverage-report` or `go-coverage`\n537: - **AND** artifact SHALL be retained for 30 days\n538: - **AND** artifact SHALL be downloadable\n539: \n540: #### Scenario: Upload E2E logs on failure\n541: - **GIVEN** the E2E workflow with test failures\n542: - **WHEN** `if: failure()` condition is met\n543: - **THEN** `e2e-logs` directory SHALL be uploaded\n544: - **AND** artifact SHALL contain component logs\n545: - **AND** artifact SHALL contain pod describes\n546: - **AND** artifact retention period SHALL be appropriate\n547: \n548: #### Scenario: No artifact upload on success\n549: - **GIVEN** the E2E workflow with passing tests\n550: - **WHEN** tests complete successfully\n551: - **THEN** `e2e-logs` artifact SHALL NOT be uploaded\n552: - **AND** disk space SHALL be saved\n553: - **AND** workflow SHALL complete without artifact\n554: \n555: #### Scenario: Artifact naming and retention\n556: - **GIVEN** workflow artifact uploads\n557: - **WHEN** artifacts are uploaded\n558: - **THEN** artifact names SHALL be descriptive\n559: - **AND** retention days SHALL be configured appropriately\n560: - **AND** artifacts SHALL be accessible from workflow run page\n561: \n562: ### Requirement: Workflow status reporting\n563: The system SHALL provide clear status reporting for pull requests and workflow runs.\n564: \n565: #### Scenario: PR check status display\n566: - **GIVEN** a pull request with workflow runs\n567: - **WHEN** workflows complete\n568: - **THEN** each workflow SHALL display check status in PR\n569: - **AND** status SHALL be passing, failing, or pending\n570: - **AND** status SHALL link to workflow run details\n571: \n572: #### Scenario: Workflow run summary\n573: - **GIVEN** a completed workflow run\n574: - **WHEN** viewing the run summary\n575: - **THEN** job steps SHALL be listed\n576: - **AND** each step SHALL show success or failure\n577: - **AND** logs SHALL be available for each step\n578: \n579: #### Scenario: Failure notification\n580: - **GIVEN** a failing workflow\n581: - **WHEN** workflow fails\n582: - **THEN** failure SHALL be reported in PR checks\n583: - **AND** failing workflow SHALL be highlighted\n584: - **AND** error details SHALL be available\n585: \n586: #### Scenario: Success notification\n587: - **GIVEN** a successful workflow\n588: - **WHEN** workflow completes successfully\n589: - **THEN** success SHALL be reported in PR checks\n590: - **AND** green checkmark SHALL be displayed\n591: - **AND** workflow SHALL not block PR merge\n592: \n593: ### Requirement: Workflow permissions and security\n594: The system SHALL use appropriate permissions and security measures for GitHub Actions workflows.\n595: \n596: #### Scenario: Workflow read permissions\n597: - **GIVEN** a workflow with default permissions\n598: - **WHEN** workflow needs to read repository content\n599: - **THEN** `contents: read` permission SHALL be sufficient\n600: - **AND** workflow SHALL be able to checkout code\n601: - **AND** workflow SHALL not have write access unless needed\n602: \n603: #### Scenario: Workflow write permissions for release\n604: - **GIVEN** the Release workflow\n605: - **WHEN** workflow needs to push images\n606: - **THEN** `contents: write` permission SHALL be required\n607: - **AND** `GITHUB_TOKEN` SHALL have registry write permissions\n608: - **AND** workflow SHALL be able to authenticate with GHCR\n609: \n610: #### Scenario: Pull request target security\n611: - **GIVEN** the Workflow Approval workflow using `pull_request_target`\n612: - **WHEN** workflow runs\n613: - **THEN** workflow SHALL run with repository permissions\n614: - **THEN** workflow SHALL NOT run with PR author permissions\n615: - **AND** security SHALL be maintained against malicious PRs\n616: \n617: #### Scenario: Secret handling\n618: - **GIVEN** workflows using secrets\n619: - **WHEN** secrets are referenced\n620: - **THEN** secrets SHALL be stored in GitHub Secrets\n621: - **THEN** secrets SHALL NOT be hardcoded in workflows\n622: - **AND** secret values SHALL be masked in logs\n623: \n624: ### Requirement: Workflow timeout and resource limits\n625: The system SHALL configure appropriate timeouts and resource limits for workflow execution.\n626: \n627: #### Scenario: Job timeout configuration\n628: - **GIVEN** workflow job configuration\n629: - **WHEN** job is defined\n630: - **THEN** timeout-minutes SHALL be set appropriately\n631: - **AND** default timeout SHALL be reasonable (e.g., 30 minutes)\n632: - **AND** long-running jobs SHALL have extended timeouts\n633: \n634: #### Scenario: E2E workflow timeout\n635: - **GIVEN** the E2E workflow job\n636: - **WHEN** job runs\n637: - **THEN** timeout-minutes SHALL account for cluster setup\n638: - **AND** timeout-minutes SHALL account for test execution\n639: - **AND** timeout-minutes SHALL account for cleanup\n640: \n641: #### Scenario: Docker build timeout\n642: - **GIVEN** the Release workflow with Docker builds\n643: - **WHEN** building multi-architecture images\n644: - **THEN** timeout SHALL be sufficient for multiple architectures\n645: - **AND** timeout SHALL account for network transfer\n646: - **AND** timeout SHALL prevent indefinite hangs\n647: \n648: #### Scenario: Timeout failure behavior\n649: - **GIVEN** a workflow job exceeding timeout\n650: - **WHEN** timeout is reached\n651: - **THEN** job SHALL be terminated\n652: - **AND** workflow SHALL report timeout failure\n653: - **AND** logs SHALL show timeout message\n654: \n655: ## Acceptance Criteria Summary\n656: \n657: 1. ✅ CI workflow builds Docker image on PR to main/release-* branches\n658: 2. ✅ Lint workflow runs golangci-lint with Go path filtering\n659: 3. ✅ Codegen check workflow verifies no drift on API/Makefile changes\n660: 4. ✅ Test coverage workflow runs race-enabled tests with coverage report\n661: 5. ✅ E2E workflow runs tests in Kind with log capture on failure\n662: 6. ✅ Python SDK tests run pytest on sdk-python changes\n663: 7. ✅ Python lint runs Ruff with Python path filtering\n664: 8. ✅ Spelling check runs codespell with file exclusions\n665: 9. ✅ Copyright check verifies headers with path filtering\n666: 10. ✅ Release workflow builds and pushes multi-architecture images to GHCR\n667: 11. ✅ Workflow approval approves runs for repeat contributors or ok-to-test label\n668: 12. ✅ Dependency update workflow periodically updates Go and Python dependencies\n669: 13. ✅ Workflow concurrency cancels in-progress runs appropriately\n670: 14. ✅ Workflow caching speeds up Go modules, Python packages, and Docker layers\n671: 15. ✅ Workflow artifacts manage logs and reports appropriately\n672: 16. ✅ Workflow status reporting provides clear PR check feedback\n673: 17. ✅ Workflow permissions use appropriate security measures\n674: 18. ✅ Workflow timeouts prevent indefinite runs\n675: \n676: ## Dependencies\n677: \n678: - GitHub Actions (Latest)\n679: - Go 1.24+ (for most workflows), Go 1.24.4 (for codegen check), Go 1.23 (for E2E)\n680: - Python 3.10+ (for Python lint), Python 3.12 (for Python SDK tests)\n681: - Docker 20.10+ with Buildx\n682: - Kind v0.30.0 (for E2E testing)\n683: - golangci-lint 1.50+ (for Go lint)\n684: - Ruff 0.1+ (for Python lint)\n685: - pytest 7.0+ (for Python testing)\n686: - codespell 2.2+ (for spelling check)\n687: - moreutils (sponge command) (for copyright check)\n688: - Base Design: `ci-cd/design.md`\n689: - Base Specification: `ci-cd/spec.md`\n690: - AR: AR-033 — Makefile 构建目标体系 (for Make target integration)\n691: - AR: AR-032 — Dockerfile 多阶段构建 (for Docker build integration)\n692: \n693: ## Breaking Changes\n694: \n695: None. This delta specification defines new GitHub Actions workflows that provide CI/CD automation for the AgentCube project. The workflows are additive and do not change existing build processes, output formats, or runtime behavior. They provide automated verification and quality checks without breaking any existing functionality, workflows, or deployments. Existing development and release processes can continue to work alongside the new CI/CD workflows.\n696: \n697: ## Security Considerations\n698: \n699: 1. **Pull Request Target Security**: The Workflow Approval workflow uses `pull_request_target` to run with repository permissions, preventing malicious PRs from abusing elevated privileges.\n700: 2. **Secret Management**: All secrets are stored in GitHub Secrets and referenced securely, never hardcoded in workflow files.\n701: 3. **Third-Party Actions**: All third-party GitHub Actions use pinned versions (e.g., `@v4`) and are regularly reviewed and updated.\n702: 4. **GHCR Authentication**: Container registry uses `GITHUB_TOKEN` for automatic authentication with appropriate permissions.\n703: 5. **First-Time Contributor Protection**: Workflow approval mechanism prevents untrusted contributors from running workflows with elevated permissions.\n704: 6. **Code Injection Prevention**: Workflows avoid dangerous operations like `eval` and validate all inputs.\n705: 7. **Dependency Verification**: Go and Python dependency updates include test verification before creating PRs.\n706: 8. **Artifact Security**: Artifacts are managed with appropriate retention periods and do not contain sensitive information.\n707: 9. **Minimal Permissions**: Workflows use the minimum required permissions (read vs write) based on their needs.\n708: 10. **Base Image Security**: Docker builds use official or trusted base images with multi-stage builds to minimize attack surface.\n709: \n710: ## Testing Strategy\n711: \n712: ### Workflow Syntax Tests\n713: - Validate all 12 workflow YAML files have correct syntax\n714: - Test all workflows can be loaded by GitHub Actions\n715: - Verify all action references are correct and use pinned versions\n716: - Test workflow triggers and event filters\n717: \n718: ### Integration Tests\n719: - Create test PRs to verify workflow triggers\n720: - Test path filtering for each workflow\n721: - Verify workflow execution on different branch patterns\n722: - Test workflow failure scenarios and error reporting\n723: - Verify PR check status reporting\n724: - Test workflow concurrency and cancellation\n725: - Test artifact upload and download\n726: \n727: ### Release Workflow Tests\n728: - Test main branch push triggers `latest` image build\n729: - Test semantic version tag triggers versioned image build\n730: - Verify multi-architecture image builds (amd64, arm64)\n731: - Test GHCR authentication and push\n732: - Verify image tagging and naming\n733: \n734: ### E2E Workflow Tests\n735: - Test Kind cluster creation and cleanup\n736: - Verify E2E test execution in cluster\n737: - Test log capture on failure\n738: - Verify cleanup logic always runs\n739: - Test artifact upload on failure\n740: \n741: ### Lint and Quality Workflow Tests\n742: - Introduce lint errors and verify workflow failure\n743: - Test code generation drift detection\n744: - Verify copyright header checking\n745: - Test spelling check with false positive handling\n746: - Verify Python lint with Ruff configuration\n747: \n748: ### Security Tests\n749: - Verify `pull_request_target` permissions\n750: - Test first-time contributor approval logic\n751: - Verify secret handling and masking\n752: - Test workflow access restrictions\n753: \n754: ### Performance Tests\n755: - Measure workflow execution times\n756: - Test caching effectiveness\n757: - Verify concurrency cancellation\n758: - Monitor resource usage\n759: \n760: ### End-to-End Tests\n761: - Complete PR lifecycle: create, checks pass, merge\n762: - Verify release workflow triggers on main merge\n763: - Test tag creation and release workflow\n764: - Verify dependency update PR creation\n765: \n766: ## References\n767: \n768: - Base Design: `ci-cd/design.md`\n769: - Base Specification: `ci-cd/spec.md`\n770: - AR-033: Makefile 构建目标体系\n771: - AR-032: Dockerfile 多阶段构建\n772: - GitHub Actions Documentation: https://docs.github.com/en/actions\n773: - GitHub Actions Best Practices: https://docs.github.com/en/actions/learn-github-actions/best-practices-for-github-actions\n774: - Docker Buildx Documentation: https://docs.docker.com/buildx/working-with-buildx/\n775: - Kind Documentation: https://kind.sigs.k8s.io/\n776: - GitHub Container Registry: https://docs.github.com/en/packages/working-with-a-github-packages-registry/working-with-the-container-registry\n\n(End of file - total 776 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Delta Specification: AR-034 — CI/CD GitHub Actions (12 workflows)\n\n## AR Metadata\n- **AR ID**: AR-034\n- **Title**: CI/CD GitHub Actions (12 workflows)\n- **Module**: .github\n- **Language**: YAML\n- **Size**: L\n- **Status**: Implementation Required\n\n## Purpose\nThis delta specification defines implementation requirements for 12 GitHub Actions workflows providing comprehensive CI/CD automation for the AgentCube project. The workflows cover build verification, linting, testing, code quality checks, end-to-end testing, Python SDK validation, container image publishing, dependency updates, and workflow approval mechanisms to ensure code quality and reliable continuous delivery.\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: CI workflow build verification\nThe system SHALL build the Workload Manager Docker image on pull requests targeting `main` or `release-*` branches using Docker Buildx.\n\n#### Scenario: Docker build verification on pull request\n- **GIVEN** a pull request to `main` or `release-*` branch","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-034/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775886003180,"end":1775886003187}}}}
